	<h1>Elizabeth Watson</h1>
	<p>Elizabeth Watson, who has Asperger&rsquo;s syndrome, was struggling  in school because of her writing abilities. Through a PACER Simon   Technology Center  consultation, she found help through an assistive device that made all the  difference. She now uses &ldquo;The Writer,&rdquo; a portable note taker that allows her to  write legibly and that reads out loud what she has written.&nbsp; </p>
	<p>Through using &ldquo;The Writer,&rdquo; Elizabeth&rsquo;s reading vocabulary score  dramatically improved from 68 to 98 percent and her language expression score  soared from 62 to 90 percent.&nbsp; Best of  all, she is now excited about writing and about her future.</p>
	<p>&nbsp;&ldquo;I hope that our  story will encourage parents who are actively seeking technology to help their  children fulfill their potential,&rdquo; says Luisa Watson, Elizabeth&rsquo;s mother. &ldquo;Thank you PACER!&rdquo; </p>
